The idea is to sum up the first row and first column as there is no way to reach to that point other than to go right or down respectively. For the rest of the grid[i][j] (for all i >1 and j >1) find the minimum of the grid-left (j-1) and grid-top (i-1) value and add to the current grid value. At the end, the minimum path sum would be the buttom last value in the grid.

```
class Solution {
    public int minPathSum(int[][] grid) {

        for(int i=1; i<grid.length; i++) {
            grid[i][0] = grid[i-1][0] + grid[i][0];
        }
        for(int j=1; j<grid[0].length; j++) {
            grid[0][j] = grid[0][j-1] + grid[0][j];
        }
        for(int i=1; i<grid.length; i++) {
            for(int j=1; j<grid[0].length; j++) {
                grid[i][j] = Math.min(grid[i-1][j], grid[i][j-1]) + grid[i][j];
            }
        }
        return grid[grid.length-1][grid[0].length-1];
    }
}
