solutions.content:
We can think of solving this problem recursively. We are standing at a current cell then the cost of reaching that cell is minimum of ( cost of reaching upper cell, cost of reaching the left cell ) + cost of current cell.

Suppose we have a fiunction called getMinSum which return minimum cost to reach. Suppose We are at 2,2 then,
getMinCost(2,2) = grid[2,2] + min(getMinCost(2,1), getMinCost(1,2));
Recursive Call, getMinCost(2,1) = grid[2,1] + min(getMinCost(2,0), getMinCost(1,1));
Recursive Call, getMinCost(2,0) = grid[2,0] + getMinCost(1,0);
Recursive Call, getMinCost(1,0) = grid[1,0] + getMinCost(0,0);
Recursive Call, getMinCost(1,0) = grid[0,0];
Recursive Call, getMinCost(1,1) = grid[1,1] + min(**getMinCost(1,0)**, getMinCost(0,1));
Recursive Call, getMinCost(0,1) = grid[0,1] + **getMinCost(0,0)** ;
Recursive Call, getMinCost(1,2) = grid[1,2] + min(**getMinCost(1,1)**, **getMinCost(0,2)**);

Now as we can see direct recursive solution is making us to calculate the same cost of reaching a cell again and again(shown in bold above). For large matrix this can make the complexity of finding a solution to be exponential.

We need to store these results of subsolutions.

For the first row and column the path sum will only be the sum of the cells till that point as there is no other way to reach the other cells.
```
