# Method #1
# Intuition & Approach 
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
- We are creating a vector of size rows and storing grid[i][0] in cur[i]
- Cur vector is used as dp vector in this method.
- Now update cur as if we are following the downward path only. 
- Use nested loop and dry run the code,
- Here we are comparing the two possibilities(Right or Downward direction)
- For reaching the cell[i][j] in matrix and update it with minimum.
- Return the answer.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n*m)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(m): m(Rows)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minPathSum(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();
        vector<int> cur(m, grid[0][0]);
        for (int i = 1; i < m; i++)
            cur[i] = cur[i - 1] + grid[i][0]; 

        for (int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
            cur[0] += grid[0][j]; 
            for (int i = 1; i < m; i++)
                cur[i] = min(cur[i - 1], cur[i]) + grid[i][j];
        }
        return cur[m - 1];
    }
};
```
