solutions.content:
# Intuition
The very simple approach is to try all paths to reach the destination from source and find the minimum path. Here i started from destionation and found the ways to reach source. (We can not apply grredy here because the elements are not uniform).

<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The first approach that hit my brain is recursion, The question allowed to moves right and down, as i am moving backwards(dest. to source) so I'm alloweded left or up moves, so the idea is to explore all the paths and find that path which has minimum sum. 
Base Condition of recursion-
1-> Suppose i reached (0,0), in this case I have to add the value present at this index.
2-> Suppose a path which takes me to an invalid index, so I did not reach to my destination, In that case I have to return something that this answer never considered in my answer, because we have to find minimum path sum here that's why i returned a big integer.
As I previously said I have two move left and up and they will be called recursively. At last minimum of them will be returned.

So the recursive solution gives TLE, then I opptimized it by using Memoization(saving recursive calls), it further reduced the time complexity but it increased the space complexity because we are using extra space(dp array).

Tabulation method is more optimized beacuse there is no recursion involved, and we saved the space taken by recursive calls in the programming stack.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    // Recursive solution(it will give TLE)
    int solve(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int i, int j){
        if(i==0 && j==0) return grid[i][j];
        if(i<0 || j<0) return 1e9;
        long left = grid[i][j]+ solve(grid, i, j-1);
        long up = grid[i][j]+ solve(grid,i-1, j );
        return min(left, up);
    }
    // MEMOIZATION
